Introduction

In this project, I have explored the data related to the dataset Medical Appointment No-show in Brazil. The patients had made the appointment, but did not show up. The whole purpose for this project is to find out what's the feature that influence patients decision.

  1. PatientId --Identification of a patient
  2. AppointmentID --Identification of each appointment
  3. Gender --Male or Female . Female is the greater proportion, woman takes way more care of they health in comparison to man.
  4. ScheduledDay --The day someone called or registered the appointment, this is before appointment of course.
  5. AppointmentDay --The day of the actuall appointment, when they have to visit the doctor.
  6. Age --How old is the patient.
  7. Neighbourhood --Where the appointment takes place.
  8. Scholarship --True of False . whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia.
  9. Hipertension --True or False
  10. Diabetes --True or False
  11. Alcoholism --True or False
  12. Handcap --True or False
  13. SMS_received --1 or more messages sent to the patient.
  14. No-show --True or False. For the No-show: it says No if the patient showed up to their appointment, and Yes if they did not show up.

The original dataset can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/joniarroba/noshowappointments/home

Initial observations:

  1. There is 110527 appointments in the dataset.
  2. There is no duplicated rows in the dataset.
  3. In this dataset, there are 11 independent variable (exclued ID) and one dependent No show.
  4. There is no missing data in this dataset
  5. Appointmentid are double than patientid which means patients has more than one appointment. Check out later.
  6. The type of ScheduledDay and AppointmentDay are object not date, therefore, I change it later on.
  7. From the ScheduledDay and AppointmentDay, I can calculate the days that patients had wait.
  8. What date is the ScheduledDay? Weekdays? Weekends?
  9. Handcap contains more than one value levels, which could be typo or the different degree of handcap. It needs to look up later.
  10. Age is interesting that it contain 104 unique level.
  11. Although there are more than 100K scheduled day, there are only 27 appointment days.

Further Observations::

Before exploratory data analysis, there are some obersvation I found:

  1. Wednesday and Tuesday had the most appointments for patient to visit doctor, Saturday had only 39, none for Sunday. 2.From the mean of "scholarship", "hipertension", "diabetes", "alcoholism", "handcap", "sms_received", which are using dummy varibles "0" and "1" to represent "True" and "Fales", we can tell the porpotion of the each feature. For "scholarship", the mean is 0.0982 which means there are 9.82% of the patients has the scholarship and so on.
  2. There are 7.19% patients has diabetes, 3.04% are alcoholism, 2.02% are handcap and 32.1% received SMS.
  3. The average age of the dataset are 37, 25% are lower than 18, 50% are below 37, and 75% are lower than 55. The oldest patients are 100 years old.
  4. This is an appointment dataset for 2016-04-29 to 2016-06-08 where patients can scheduled the since 2015-11-10 to 2016-06-08.
  5. The average days for patients to wait for the appoinment is 10 days, 50% of patients wait for less than 4 days and 75% are less than 15 days. The longest had wait for 179 days.

Exploratory Data Analysis

What factors are important for us to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment? For answering this quesion, I would focus on the questions below.

  • How many patients no shows in this dataset?
  • What's the age and gender are the patients who did not show up.
  • Where are the most and lest no shows cases occur?
  • Does the waiting days effect the no-show? Or the day of weeks?
  • The patient who made more than one appointment are tend to be higher chance to no show?
  • Does the Scholarship and all the illness related the no shows?
  • Dose the SMS messige helps patient to show up?

In [716]:
# Make two dataframe
Yes = df.query('no_show =="Yes"')
No = df.query('no_show =="No"')

YF = Yes.query('gender == "F"').age_levels.value_counts() / len(Yes.query('gender== "F"').age_levels)
YM = Yes.query('gender == "M"').age_levels.value_counts() / len(Yes.query('gender== "M"').age_levels)

width =0.35
ind = np.arange(len(YF))
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
bar1 = plt.bar(ind, YF, width, color='pink', alpha=.7, label='Female')
bar2 = plt.bar(ind + width, YM, width, color='skyblue', alpha=.7, label='Male')

# title and labels

plt.ylabel('Proportion',fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Age levels',fontsize=16)
plt.title('The Age proportion for No Shows',y=1.05,fontsize=18)
locations = ind + width / 2  # xtick locations
labels = ['0-15', '16-35', '36-55', '56-98']  # xtick labels
plt.xticks(locations, labels,fontsize=14)



# legend
plt.legend(loc = 'best',fontsize=14);

From the chart above, we can see that regardless genders, the proportion of 0-15 years old has the most no show among all other age levels. The proportion of no show decreases with increasing age levels for females. Same thing for Man, but at the age level in 15 to 35 and 35 to 55 are close. Female has higher proportion to be no shows in 0-15 and 16-35 than male, and for 36-55 and 56-98, male has higher chance to be no show.

Most of the patients make an appointment in the same day and only 4.65% did not show up. Since the data set are strong skew to right, we only investigate the waiting period from same day to 20 days. Above 20 day could be miss lead due to the small sample size. In 20 days, it seems that the percentage of no shows are growing along with increase of days. At the 20 days, the percentage of no-show is 34.77%.

Conclusions

In this project, I had done the data wrangling, cleaning, and exploratory data analysis(EDA) to explore the potiential relationship between most of the variables and outcome variable "No show". This is not the end of the analysis, instead, this project is ready for the further analysis to discover more.

Findings:

  1. Around 20% of the patient schedual a appoiment but no show.
  2. This dataset contains the appointment for 2016-04-29 to 2016-06-08, where patients can scheduled the since 2015-11-10 to 2016-06-08.
  3. The average age of patients are 37. 75% of the patients are lower than 55, and the oldest age is 100 years old.
  4. The rate of not showing decrease along the age growth, female tend to be having more no show than male under 35 years old, the tend inverse above 35 years old.
  5. The location of the hosipital the contain highest no show rate is SANTOS DUMONT (28.91%), follow by SANTA CECLIA (27,46%), and SANTA CLARA (26,48%).
  6. Most of the patients made an appointment in the same day and only 4.65% did not show up.
  7. The average waiting days for an appoinment is 10 days, 50% of the patients waited for less than 4 days and most of them waited less than 15 days. The longest one had wait for 179 days.
  8. In 20 days waiting, it seems that the rate of no shows are growing along with increase of days.
  9. Wednesday and Tuesday are the most popular dates for patients to made appointment, Saturday has only 39 times, and None for Sunday. The no-show seems happend less frequency on Thursday.
  10. For more appointments one patient made, no-show rate did not go along with it. It manitain the same amount of rate around 20%.
  11. It seems the relationship between no show and illness or Scholarship are not clear due to the small sample size of the patients who has the illness.
  12. The SMS message does help the patient to show up.
